        <title>Some Lessons From K–12 for Teachers and Administrators</title>
        <contents>&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Zwiers et al. (2014) uncovered shifts in instruction and assessment that are needed to help diverse students succeed. The advent of more rigorous standards has pushed teachers to find more ways to support academic English learners.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Shift from access to ownership.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Shift from pieces to wholes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Shift from a sole focus on content to placing equal emphases on language, literacy, and content.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Shift from individual to collaborative.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Shift from playing school to learning.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Shift from "direct" to "less direct" teaching.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Shift from testing to assessment and beyond.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Shift from silos to sustainable systems&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</contents>
