        <title>Some Lessons From K–12 for Teachers and Administrators</title>
        <contents>&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;&lt;img src="@@PLUGINFILE@@/learners%20in%20a%20class%20at%20computers.png" alt="learners in a class at computers" style="float: right; margin: 5px 15px;" width="250" /&gt;The authors remind us that teachers and programs are along a continuum in their realization of these shifts. As you read the &lt;a href="http://aldnetwork.org/news/eight-essential-shifts-teaching-new-standards-academic-english-learners" title="Eight Essential Shifts" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Eight Essential Shifts for Teaching New Standards to Academic English Learners&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, answer the following questions:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;&lt;em&gt;What do you think these shifts mean for your program?&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;&lt;em&gt;Where is your program on a continuum, where 1 is minimally focused on academic language and 10 is highly focused on academic language?&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: medium;"&gt;Based on what you have learned in this unit, now turn to a short a three-item action plan for your program in the next activity.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: xx-small;"&gt;From &lt;i&gt;Common Core Standards in Diverse Classrooms &lt;/i&gt;Jeff Zwiers, Susan O’Hara, and Robert Pritchard, copyright © 2014, reproduced with permission of Stenhouse Publishers. &lt;a href="http://www.stenhouse.com" title="stenhouse" target="_blank"&gt;www.stenhouse.com&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</contents>
